    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Dangerous Living</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Thomas J Carolan Jr letter, commenting on May 30 article on concern over wildfires in West, says government should not bail out people who choose to live in fragile landscapes</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Population Shift in the West Raises Wildfire Concerns'' (front page, May 30):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Population Shift in the West Raises Wildfire Concerns'' (front page, May 30):</p>
        <p>The growing propensity of Americans to take up residence in fragile landscapes -- whether forests, mountains, deserts, wetlands or barrier islands -- is, or should be, a source of national concern. Their expectation, shared apparently by certain elected politicians, that the rest of us taxpayers should bail them out when disaster strikes or even threatens is, or should be, a national disgrace.</p>
        <p>THOMAS J. CAROLAN JR.  Silver Spring, Md., May 30, 2000</p>
      </block>
